04528nam a22005415i 9780822397915DE-B159720210225050953.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210225t19961996ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223979157 a10.1515/97808223979152doi  a(DE-B1597)552704  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aML3534b.G7 1996 7aMUS0350002bisacsh04a781.662221 aGracyk, Theodore, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRhythm and Noise :bAn Aesthetics of Rock /cTheodore Gracyk. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1996] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 That Wild, Thin Mercury Sound: Ontology -- t2 I'll Be Your Mirror: Recording and Representing -- t3 Record Consciousness -- t4 Pump Up the Volume -- t5 Jungle Rhythms and the Big Beat -- t6 Adorno, Jazz, and the Reception of Popular Music -- t7 Romanticizing Rock Music -- t8 Sign O' the Times: Ideology and Aesthetics -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aYou know it when you hear it, but can you say what it is? How you know? Why you either love or loathe it? What makes it original or derivative? To a music that tends to render its aficionados and detractors equally inarticulate, Theodore Gracyk brings a rare critical clarity. His book tells us once and for all what makes rock music rock. A happy marriage of aesthetic theory and the aesthetic practice that moved a generation, Rhythm and Noise is the only thorough-going account of rock as a distinct artistic medium rather than a species of popular culture.What’s in a name? “Rock” or “Rock ’n’ Roll?” Grayck argues that rock and roll is actually a performance style, one in a number of musical styles comprising rock. What distinguishes rock, Gracyk tells us, is how it is mediated by technology: The art is in the recording. The lesson is a heady one, entailing a tour through the history of rock music from Elvis Presley’s first recordings in 1954 to Kurt Cobain’s suicide in 1994. Gracyk takes us through key recordings, lets us hear what rock musicians and their critics have to say, shows us how other kinds of music compare, and gives us the philosophical background to make more than passing sense of the medium. His work takes up the common myths and stereotypes about rock, popular and academic, and focuses on the features of the music that electrify fans and consistently generate controversy. When Elvis came to town, did southern sheriffs say that rock was barbaric and addictive? Well so did Theodor Adorno, in his way, and Allan Bloom, in his, and Gracyk takes aim at this charge as it echoes through the era of recorded music. He looks at what rock has to do with romanticism and, even more, with commercialism. And he questions the orthodoxy of making grand distinctions between “serious” and “popular” art.Keenly attuned to the nuances of music and of all the ways that we can think about it, this exhilarating book tunes us in, as no other has, to the complex role of rock in American culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aMusicy20th centuryxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 0aPopular culturexHistoryy20th century. 0aRock musicxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Rock.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082239791540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822397915423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822397915.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles